@kalefranz I'd like to bump on this one.

There are two scenarios where this is valuable: very large conda packages (100s of MB), and space-constrained systems (think VMs and containers).  In both cases some action like a first-time `conda install anaconda python=3.5` is going to chew up maybe 1.5-2GB of disk space.  That may be **way** over what is available and everything will go badly wrong (and not just for Anaconda) if so.  It seems reasonable to include a package size **hint** inside the package meta-data, and if this is available to use it to sum up all "hints" for packages that are going to be downloaded and installed for the first time.  If there is no hint, then just assume that it will be, say, 50% bigger than the download tarball (or whatever factor).  Then conda can make a reasonable estimate of how much disk space it is going to require i) on the partition where the download happens (package cache); and ii) on the partition where the package will be installed.

For packages that are already downloaded and expanded in the package cache, conda could use the same mechanics in scenarios where the content is being copied to the target env, rather than linked, and warn or abort if there is insufficient space.

