When RiveScript encounters a `<call>` tag, it runs that function and expects a string response that it can substitute into the reply in place of the original `<call>` tag. So if your program is waiting for `reply()` to return before reading the response to you out loud, this won't get to happen until after that `<call>` tag has finished.

I have two ideas for you:

* Program a special case into your bot that you handle *outside* of RiveScript. For example, instead of using a `<call>` tag, make up your own custom tag like `<return_home>` and put that in the reply. The result from `rs.reply()` would contain the literal text `"<return_home>"` and you could look for this and handle it accordingly.

    ```python
    reply = rs.reply(user, message)
    text_to_speech.say(reply)  # read reply out loud however you do that
    if "<return_home>" in reply:  # look for your custom tag
        return_home()  # run this function here after the reply's been read
    ```

* Look into ways to make your object macro asynchronous. Python 3 has [asyncio](https://docs.python.org/3/library/asyncio.html) which has also been backported to Python 2, or [Twisted](https://twistedmatrix.com/trac/) might be another option. The general idea is that your object macro should somehow be able to "fork" and "run a function in the background", but be allowed to `return` a string right away. This way the `<call>` function can return quickly and RiveScript can return a string response, and your forked function runs in the background.

    However, I haven't done any async programming in Python and don't know the exact methods for how to do this. As a JavaScript example, this is equivalent to what I'm thinking:

    ```javascript
    function needsStringResponse(message) {
        // setTimeout "forks" and runs in the background asynchronously
        setTimeout(function() {
            console.log("logged after 5 seconds");
        }, 5000);

        // this `return` will return a string immediately, and then
        // 5 seconds later the function above runs.
        return "a string";
    }
    ```

The automain function behaves the same as any other captured function, so there, too, you need to pass all the config variables that you want to use. 

You have two options to make this nicer: 1) use nested configuration values or 2) use the `_config`.

1) You can use nesting in your config like this:
``` python
@ex.config
def config():
    ....
    optimizer = {
        'name': 'Adam',
        'params':  {'lr': 1e-4}
    }
```
And then you only need to pass `optimizer` to any function. Note that in this setting it is still easy to set the learning rate from the commandline using `with optimizer.params.lr=100`.

2) The special `_config` argument can be accepted by any captured function and contains the entire configurations. So this should work too (although it is less neat IMHO):
``` python
@ex.automain
def main(_config):
    mode = 'train'
    # Network initialisation:
    agent = Net()  # Define agent as an object of class Net
    opt = getattr(optim,_config['optimizer'])(agent.parameters(), **_config['optimizer_params'])
```
Hope that helps.

